items.content_html:
@MikeIsaac I think I disagree on this one: (1) I don't think there was any sort of consensus that AGI (a terribly defined term, I agree) would happen in the past three years, including in statements from the CEOs of the big labs, (2) I don't see there being a major downward revision of expectations of AI impact, either from analysts or academics studying this field. A lot of stuff is happening faster than expected as well (Math Olympiad, among others)/

That doesn't eliminate the fact that there are plenty of people hyping AI stuff, anticipating rapid job loss, AGI, etc, but I don't think that was the consensus view outside of Twitter circles.

AGI predictions have steadily been in the range of 2030-2034 or so, for what that is worth, ever since the release of ChatGPT.

@NestorLRamos @elonmusk @Tesla Three years from now, when there are millions of robotaxis on the streets and maybe even a few Optimus humanoid robots, everybody is going to recognize that Tesla AI is way better than anybody else's AI. I know this to be true today, but in three years, every human being in the world is going to know Tesla AI is better.

This removes complexity from the buying decision and removes a safety problem, because the old Autopilot wasn't safe. They should just stick to the plan: offer manual driving or FSD, with no in-between, and charge the $100. People will either pay it or they won't.

But I think in three years, every human is going to want it. Every Tesla owner is going to be aware that they are giving up a lot of value if they don't pay for the subscription. So, I say it's a good thing to simplify. 

Yes, we will lose maybe a couple of customers to Toyota because they give free ADAS (Advanced Driver Assistance Systems), but I don't think people buy cars because of ADAS. They buy cars to save lives; they buy cars to be more convenient. That is FSD. FSD is far superior to anything Toyota, Mercedes, or anybody else has (other than the Chinese).

3. You're never going to want to drive manually ever again.

That's what people aren't getting. I'm already there; I am never going to drive my car manually. It's over.

items.content:
"One of the clearest ancient parallels is the Roman Empire's practice of debasing its currency, which functioned as a form of hidden inflation. 

Emperors like Nero began reducing the silver content in coins (e.g., the denarius dropped from nearly pure silver at 4.5 grams to just 2% silver by the third century), while maintaining the coins' face value and size initially. This increased the money supply without overt tax hikes, but it eroded purchasing power over time. 

Quality degradation extended beyond money: as inflation rose, goods like bread and wine were often adulterated with cheaper fillers, and infrastructure maintenance declined, contributing to widespread perceptions of societal decay. 

Historians link this to broader decline, including economic instability, loss of public trust, and eventual collapse factors like barbarian invasions‚Äîechoing modern complaints about "everything feeling worse" despite stable official CPI figures adjusted for "hedonic quality."

items.content:
@dionizije_fa @wholemars When Instagram was purchased for $1 billion it had zero sales, zero profits (huge losses actually), only 14 employees, no assets. 

Yet today it would be worth hundreds of billions. 

I never look at what companies did last quarter (the numbers this last quarter sucked, which is why I see a possible disaster coming). 

I look at how relevant a company is. 

And I've studied its American (and Chinese) competitors and I see Tesla is gaining in relevance, not losing it.

I also don't play short term games. I never can figure those out, since owning Tesla it has gone down something like nine times more than 40%. 

I bet on companies that I want to own for at least a decade and this is at the top of my list of those. 

In 1999 Amazon was $112.
In 2001 it went down to $6. 

Buying and holding at either price looks like a genius move today. 

I'll just hold through any moves, either negative or positive. 

Playing other games is valid. Everyone is a different investor. I'm one of those who buys and holds. The past few years that has hurt me. Others sold their Tesla and played other games and made a lot more money than I did. 

One of my things that I do when investing is "what kind of world do I want to see happen?"

Cars killed two of my high school friends. Autonomy will fix that. Part of my thesis is understanding the auto industry and seeing no one else invested in making that happen. 

Someday that will pay off and if it doesn't, at least I see a ton of Teslas here in Silicon Valley so the future got better than the one I grew up in. Our roads are already safer, even for those who drive gas cars because of Tesla. 

That's worth investing in for me.

I think we're 100% in some kind of hyperinflationary state

But the hyperinflation is hidden from prices and instead shows up in the extreme decrease in quality of almost every product and service

We're in an asset boom where stock prices look like they're growing but they just show the underlying value or currencies is rapidly dropping

You can't measure this inflation easily because quality is subjectively perceived and not included in inflation data (how would you?) but it's happening for sure

10 years ago I'd eat mostly processed food, high carbs (like most ppl), br...
items.content:
What's odd (or well not)

10 years ago I'd eat mostly processed food, high carbs (like most ppl), bread, croissants, always lattes when I had coffee, pasta etc, protein was not a priority at all, and except for some bodyweight exercises and walking I didn't really work out at all, also I was very skinny like 50kg/110lbs

I'd feel tired regularly and would take afternoon naps, also quite anxious and regularly depressed, but I thought I was healthy though (I mean I wasn't fat? So I'm healthy? That was my logic)

Then I started going gym slowly ramping up to 4 times per week, lifting weights + cardio, and eating mostly clean and high protein like fresh meat, egg, vegetables, fruit, water, black coffee, and dark chocolate if I wanted candy, and I gained 60% weight (mostly muscle mass) and now I'm ~80kg/176lbs with 14% body fa

And nowadays I'm 10 years older than then but you wouldn't be able to get me to fall asleep in afternoon, I'm never lethargic, tired, almost never sick, never anxious, not depressed, almost always quite excited and energetic

So yes I agree with this, most people's hormonal system isn't functioning as it should, or would 100 years ago when the quality of our food wasn't this bad, most food in supermarkets and even restaurants now is trash and bad for you

Luckily the fix is quite easy: eat a clean diet of whole foods like meat, eggs, veg, fruit, black coffee, water, and hit the gym, lift weights and cardio and see how you feel in 3 months, at least this worked for me!
